text: This is a real article, that the NYT paid someone actual money to write
Why?
(Pssst…have I ever mentioned that people are the worst? Pass it on…)
Holy shit, kids are frustrating. I cannot seem to get my older two over this stint of lying they've started and lying is one of my all-time highest rage-inducing pet peeves.
Ooh, that's bad.
Paisley took some candy out of one of the bulk candy bins at the grocery store the other week and I told her to put it back.
It was some distance away, but I watched her. She walked over to it. Looked at the bin. Stuck the candy in her pocket and then came back and *told me* that she put it back.
What ages?
I was not a happy daddy.
Paisley is 4.
My two are 8 and 6
And the most annoying part is that it's always over small little stuff that I wouldn't get mad about
But then you layer the lying onto it and then I'm mad
My daughter is almost four and she sometimes... struggles with the truth.
6 is probably followinng 8's lead... but as far as lieing goes oof, at 8 is rough
for 4 year olds its a sign of intellegence, and not much else sadly
Thanks?
Paisley no
well, when you're 4 morals aren't really a thing
She also preemptively lied about taking a picture.
I walk into the living room and her hand goes behind her back. "Nothing!"
I'm like "..."
I didn't even ask, and I wouldn't have cared.
I mean, kids are still learning to know that other people have feelings well into 6 years old...
But now I care.
I'm still learning that and I'm 31.
yuuuuup
I learned it, I just don't care :smile:
/ sarcasm
:no_mouth:
Don't you no mouth at me, sir :neutral_face:
:face_with_hand_over_mouth:
What other no-mouth emojis are there?
:mask:
:high_heel:
Also, I got yelled at for talking about separating without a degree today O.o
from the military? they don't want to have to train someone new
I mean, my tour here ends in December along with my service, so they're already resolved to that
Actually, I've told them I won't do certain parts of the job anymore because the office in general has been too reliant on the military in general
It was a fun conversation with my Master Sergeant
Seth, I know I mentioned it once, but I’m still so proud of you for doing what is best for you
for shizzle
Well, now I have to sit down with my Chief and come up with a plan XD Which, ironically, is what the separation folks are supposed to do, but my assignment is... Weird
Elaborate?

Separating from the military is normally not a "fast" thing. You have to go to classes and do a bunch of stuff before you're out. The classes are like resume writing, job finding, etc., because some people join right out of HS and just don't know how to do those things.
Huh, that makes a lot of sense. I never thought about that
So you're skipping TAP completely?
No, I was going to go, but I got dragged to my Chief, too
Also, I got out without a degree (other than my CCAF)... It's not actually that big a deal if you're from a technical career field like you are, I would say.
I could be making 6 figures right now if I'd gone to a more boring/dangerous-in-a-non-fun way with mine, and I know with networking stuff it's about the same if you come bundled with a clearance.
My Chief was actually the only person who really was kind of a jerk about me deciding to get out.
Which really got to me, honestly.

I figured I wasn't going to be  GS-15 or anything, but I have a clearance, I've been in the building for 3 years and I know quite a few people. I didn't think it'd be terrible. And worse comes to worse, I have my GI bill if I couldn't find anything and decided to finish my degree
You're going federal, then? I thought last time I talked with you you were looking at that contractor life.
Although yeah, GS-15 would be pretty much impossible. A Captain I worked with got it right out of Security Forces, and everyone thought that was a miracle. He did already have his Masters, though.
I like the stability of federal. Plus I get to roll my service into my retirement that way
Yep
If I can't or don't find anything, though, I have some friends in companies nearby
It's pricey, though. Cost me $4K
You already looking around on USAJOBS, then?
One of the Chief Warrants I worked with is working with ForcePoint / Raytheon now
Yeah, along with some other places because my building is dumb and doesn't list their jobs there
That's fairly common when it comes to some of the places that want TS stuff. Excepted Service is what I think they call it.

In any case, if you're just moving down the hall I'm sure others can give you better/more direct advice than I can, but let me know if you want help with Federal jobs stuff. The biggest thing is that it may look like shit, but use the USAJOBS resume builder if you're going through there. It follows the hiring checklist by default.
Yeah, I work at an agency in the DC area :stuck_out_tongue:
Yeah, my brother has been bugging me to go do that. I just enjoy the Emergency Management life too much to do it.
Agencies have EM :stuck_out_tongue:
I've actually worked with the team in my building a few times

I think I thought we were just talking about a different agency. FEMA is what I'm staring at pretty hard right now, but I could probably find an EM job with DOD, DOE, or FBI. Those just come with... a lot of baggage when it comes to the mission.
Generally when people aren't mentioning the actual acronym, however, there's a different type of thing going on.  = )
Maybe I'm just hyper OPSEC minded :wink:
For sure.
